│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe `slp-vectorizer` is crashing with an    │
│ assertion failure: `SubVectorsMask.size() == CommonMask.size()`. This assertion is in      │
│ `BoUpSLP::ShuffleCostEstimator::finalize`, a function responsible for calculating the cost │
│ of shuffling vector elements. The assertion indicates that two internal masks used to      │
│ describe how sub-vectors are combined have different sizes, which should not happen in a   │
│ well-formed operation.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log is quite           │
│ revealing. The vectorizer identifies a set of 16 `icmp` instructions as candidates for     │
│ vectorization. It then works its way up the data dependency graph, building a \"tree\" of  │
│ instructions to vectorize together.\n\n- It successfully bundles the `icmp`, `freeze`, and │
│ `or` instructions.\n- It then reaches the `trunc` instructions. The operands for these     │
│ `trunc`s are a mix of different `lshr` and `xor` instructions.\n- The log shows `SLP:      │
│ Shuffle for reused scalars.` This is a key moment. The vectorizer has identified that some │
│ of the scalar inputs to the `trunc` instructions are identical (e.g., multiple lanes use   │
│ the same constant `0`). It's trying to be clever and build a smaller vector of unique      │
│ scalars, then shuffle them into the correct lanes.\n- It attempts to build a bundle of 13  │
│ unique scalar inputs. However, it then logs `SLP: We are not able to schedule this         │
│ bundle!`. This is the first sign of trouble. The scheduling logic rejected this plan.\n-   │
│ The vectorizer then falls back to a different strategy: `SLP: Gathering due to C,S,B,O,    │
│ small shuffle.`. This is where it tries to form smaller groups of scalars.\n- The crash    │
│ occurs shortly after, when calculating the cost of this new, more complex gathering        │
│ strategy. The log shows it's in the middle of calculating the cost for the `trunc` bundle  │
│ (bundle `Idx: 3`) when the assertion hits.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe core of    │
│ the problem lies in how the SLP vectorizer handles the fallback from a failed \"reused     │
│ scalars\" shuffle.\n\n1.  The vectorizer first optimistically tries to form a single       │
│ vector from all unique scalar inputs (`%xor108.i.i.i`, `%cond.i1002.2.i.i.i`, and `lshr    │
│ i64 0, 0`). This plan is rejected by the scheduler (`isLegalToSchedule`), likely due to    │
│ the complexity of the dependencies.\n\n2.  It then enters a fallback path where it tries   │
│ to group the scalars into smaller, more manageable sub-vectors. It identifies two main     │
│ groups: one for the constant `0` (`lshr i64 0, 0`) and another for the non-constant        │
│ values.\n\n3.  When it processes the non-constant group, it correctly identifies that      │
│ `%xor108.i.i.i` and `%cond.i1002.2.i.i.i` are actually the same value (since `lshr val, 0` │
│ is a no-op). It decides to create a sub-vector containing just this single unique          │
│ value.\n\n4.  Here's the bug: When creating the shuffle mask for this single-element       │
│ sub-vector, the code in `ShuffleCostEstimator::finalize` incorrectly uses the size of the  │
│ *original* full group of non-constant scalars (which was 5) to initialize the              │
│ `SubVectorsMask`. However, the `CommonMask` for this operation is correctly sized to 1, as │
│ it's building a vector with one element.\n\n5.  This leads to the assertion failure:       │
│ `SubVectorsMask` has a size of 5, while `CommonMask` has a size of 1. The code that builds │
│ the shuffle for the sub-vector did not correctly account for the fact that the number of   │
│ unique scalars within that sub-group could be smaller than the number of lanes it          │
│ feeds.\n\nThe fix is to ensure that when we are building the shuffle mask for a            │
│ sub-vector, we use the size of the *final, unique* set of scalars for that sub-vector, not │
│ the size of the initial group of lanes.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is a   │
│ one-line change in `SLPVectorizer.cpp`. We need to adjust the size of the `SubVectorsMask` │
│ to match the actual number of unique scalars being shuffled in the                         │
│ sub-vector.\n\n```cpp\n// llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n\n10874:    //  │
│ Build a shuffle for the subvector.\n10875:    SmallVector<int>                             │
│ SubVectorsMask(SubVector.size(), PoisonMaskElem);\n10876:    for (const auto &It :         │
│ SubVector)\n10877:      SubVectorsMask[It.second] = It.first;\n```\n\nThe line `10875`     │
│ should be changed to use `UniqueScalars.size()` instead of `SubVector.size()`."})          │
