│                                                                                            │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                            │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `slp-vectorizer` is crashing with an assertion failure: `SubVectorsMask.size() ==      │
│ CommonMask.size()`. This assertion is in `BoUpSLP::ShuffleCostEstimator::finalize`, a      │
│ function responsible for calculating the cost of shuffling vector elements. The assertion  │
│ indicates that two internal masks used to describe how sub-vectors are combined have       │
│ different sizes, which should not happen in a well-formed operation.                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `opt` log is quite revealing. The vectorizer identifies a set of 16 `icmp`             │
│ instructions as candidates for vectorization. It then works its way up the data dependency │
│ graph, building a "tree" of instructions to vectorize together.                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ - It successfully bundles the `icmp`, `freeze`, and `or` instructions.                     │
│ - It then reaches the `trunc` instructions. The operands for these `trunc`s are a mix of   │
│ different `lshr` and `xor` instructions.                                                   │
│ - The log shows `SLP: Shuffle for reused scalars.` This is a key moment. The vectorizer    │
│ has identified that some of the scalar inputs to the `trunc` instructions are identical    │
│ (e.g., multiple lanes use the same constant `0`). It's trying to be clever and build a     │
│ smaller vector of unique scalars, then shuffle them into the correct lanes.                │
│ - It attempts to build a bundle of 13 unique scalar inputs. However, it then logs `SLP: We │
│ are not able to schedule this bundle!`. This is the first sign of trouble. The scheduling  │
│ logic rejected this plan.                                                                  │
│ - The vectorizer then falls back to a different strategy: `SLP: Gathering due to C,S,B,O,  │
│ small shuffle.`. This is where it tries to form smaller groups of scalars.                 │
│ - The crash occurs shortly after, when calculating the cost of this new, more complex      │
│ gathering strategy. The log shows it's in the middle of calculating the cost for the       │
│ `trunc` bundle (bundle `Idx: 3`) when the assertion hits.                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The core of the problem lies in how the SLP vectorizer handles the fallback from a failed  │
│ "reused scalars" shuffle.                                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ 1.  The vectorizer first optimistically tries to form a single vector from all unique      │
│ scalar inputs (`%xor108.i.i.i`, `%cond.i1002.2.i.i.i`, and `lshr i64 0, 0`). This plan is  │
│ rejected by the scheduler (`isLegalToSchedule`), likely due to the complexity of the       │
│ dependencies.                                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ 2.  It then enters a fallback path where it tries to group the scalars into smaller, more  │
│ manageable sub-vectors. It identifies two main groups: one for the constant `0` (`lshr i64 │
│ 0, 0`) and another for the non-constant values.                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ 3.  When it processes the non-constant group, it correctly identifies that `%xor108.i.i.i` │
│ and `%cond.i1002.2.i.i.i` are actually the same value (since `lshr val, 0` is a no-op). It │
│ decides to create a sub-vector containing just this single unique value.                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ 4.  Here's the bug: When creating the shuffle mask for this single-element sub-vector, the │
│ code in `ShuffleCostEstimator::finalize` incorrectly uses the size of the *original* full  │
│ group of non-constant scalars (which was 5) to initialize the `SubVectorsMask`. However,   │
│ the `CommonMask` for this operation is correctly sized to 1, as it's building a vector     │
│ with one element.                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ 5.  This leads to the assertion failure: `SubVectorsMask` has a size of 5, while           │
│ `CommonMask` has a size of 1. The code that builds the shuffle for the sub-vector did not  │
│ correctly account for the fact that the number of unique scalars within that sub-group     │
│ could be smaller than the number of lanes it feeds.                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to ensure that when we are building the shuffle mask for a sub-vector, we use   │
│ the size of the *final, unique* set of scalars for that sub-vector, not the size of the    │
│ initial group of lanes.                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is a one-line change in `SLPVectorizer.cpp`. We need to adjust the size of the     │
│ `SubVectorsMask` to match the actual number of unique scalars being shuffled in the        │
│ sub-vector.                                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ 10874:    // Build a shuffle for the subvector.                                            │
│ 10875:    SmallVector<int> SubVectorsMask(SubVector.size(), PoisonMaskElem);               │
│ 10876:    for (const auto &It : SubVector)                                                 │
│ 10877:      SubVectorsMask[It.second] = It.first;                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ The line `10875` should be changed to use `UniqueScalars.size()` instead of                │
│ `SubVector.size()`.                                                                        │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ ## Suspected Code Locations ##                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ Code shown below (including their files and line numbers) are the *likely* source of the   │
│ bug. However, the actual fix may involve other parts of the codebase as well.              │
│ You should use the provided tools to explore the codebase for more context and edit the    │
│ codebase as needed to fix the bug.                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
