│ An analysis of the bug report indicates a crash in the SLP vectorizer's cost estimation    │
│ logic. The root cause is an incorrect size calculation for `SubVectorsMask` during a       │
│ fallback scenario where the vectorizer attempts to group unique scalar inputs into         │
│ sub-vectors. When a sub-group of scalars is further deduplicated, the mask for shuffling   │
│ them is created with the original, larger size, while the common mask for the resulting    │
│ unique vector is created with the new, smaller size. This size mismatch triggers the       │
│ assertion `SubVectorsMask.size() == CommonMask.size()`.                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to ensure that when `SubVectorsMask` is created for a sub-vector, its size is   │
│ based on the number of unique scalars in that sub-vector, not the number of lanes it will  │
│ feed. This is achieved by changing the size argument in the `SubVectorsMask` constructor   │
│ from `SubVector.size()` to `UniqueScalars.size()`.                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now apply this change.                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
